<section xml:id="sec_electric-field" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>Electric Field</title>
		
    <video youtube="wYKAWt9IBHk"><description>Introducing the electric field.</description></video>
	
<p>
Charged particles are all around us and each charge generates an electric field. Electric fields exist everywhere in space. The motion of charged objects through space is governed by any pre-existing electric fields. We can begin to understand this motion by analyzing the force applied to a charged object due to an electric field.
</p>

<definition>
	<title>
	Electric field
	</title>
		<statement>
		
			<p>
			
			</p>
			
			<p>
			The <term> electric field </term> is a <em> vector field </em> that tells a charged object what force to feel.
			</p>
		</statement>
</definition>

<definition>
	<title>
	Electric force
	</title>
		<statement>
			<p>
			
			</p>

			<p>
			The <term>electric force</term> on a point-like object (test charge) is the product of the object's charge and the electric field at the location of the object: <me>\vec{F}_E = q_{\text{test}} \vec{E}</me>
			</p>
		</statement>
	</definition>
	
<p>
Charged particles interact with each other through electric fields. Like the gravitational force, the electric force is a long range force, as opposed to a contact force. The electric and gravitational fields are responsible for mediating the force interaction between charges and masses, respectively.  Much of what we do in exploring electric fields has a direct analogue with gravitational fields. Keep this in mind as we progress through the next few chapters. 
</p>

<p>

</p>
<p>
Each and every electric charge generates its own electric field. We can think of the electric field as a physical alteration of the space around a charge which describes the influence of that charge on other charges in their vicinity. We usually call the charge generating the field the <em>source charge</em>, and represent it mathematically as <m> q_{\text{source}}</m>, and the charge experiencing the field the <em>test charge</em>, and represent it as <m> q_{\text{test}}</m>. A source charge never feels a force from its own field. It would violate conservation of energy for a charge to be able to exert a force on itself through its own field. Eventually, we would like to drop the subscript notation and just be able to describe charges using the simpler notation, <m>q</m>, being able to tell from context which is the charge creating the field and which is the charge experiencing the field. 
</p>

<exercises>
		<title>
		The Electric Field of a Single Point Charge
		</title>
</exercises>

<definition xml:id="point_charge">
	<title>
	Single Point Charge
	</title>
		<statement>
		
			<p>
			
			</p>
			
			<p>
			The electric field of a single point charge is defined mathematically as <me> \vec{E}(r) = \frac{1}{4 \pi \epsilon_{0}} \frac {q}{r^2} \hat{r}</me> where <m> q </m> represents the source charge generating the field, <m> r </m> is the distance from the charge to the location we want to know the magnitude of the field, <m> \hat{r} </m> is a unit vector that points radially away from the charge, and <m> \epsilon_{0} = 8.85 \times 10^{-12} \frac{\mathrm{C^2}}{\mathrm{Nm^2}}</m> is the <em> permittivity constant </em>. 
			</p>
		</statement>
</definition>


<p>
To understand the above definition, let's use a visual representation to be precise about what each symbol of the equation means physically. Consider a charge <m> q </m>, represented in the figure below by a positive charge, and a point in space <m> P </m> a distance <m> r </m> away from charge <m> q </m>. The vector symbol above the <m> E</m> within the notation <m> \vec{E}(r) </m>, tells us that the electric field is a vector and it depends on, or is a function of, the distance <m> r </m> from the center of the charge <m> q </m> that creates the field. The field is defined at any point in space around the charge, and its magnitude changes with the inverse square of distance from that charge. To find the direction of the field, we use the unit vector <m> \hat{r} </m> which always points from center of the charge radially outward.  When we multiply the magnitude of the electric field by the unit vector <m> \hat{r} </m>, we can find the direction of the field at point <m> P </m>. Recall that a unit vector itself has magnitude <m> |\hat{r}|=1.0 </m> and so multiplying the equation by <m> \hat{r} </m> does not change the overall magnitude, it only imparts a directionality to the field at that point. If we chose a different point in space around the charge, the electric field, both the magnitude and the direction, would be different depending on that position. This is yet another reason for using the notation <m> \vec{E}(r) </m> suggesting the electric field is a <em > function of position </em>. 
</p>
