	<exercises>
		<title>
		The Permittivity Constant
		</title>
	</exercises>
	
	<p>
Let's discuss the permittivity constant, <m> \epsilon_{0} = 8.85 \times 10^{-12} \frac{\mathrm{C^2}}{\mathrm{Nm^2}}</m>. Electric fields are generated by charges. If there is other matter around that charge, for example air or wood or water, that matter can affect how the electric field is <em> permitted </em> to exist. The constant <m> \epsilon_{0} </m> (pronounced "epsilon naught") is a constant of proportionality which scales how the magnitude of the electric field is related to charge and distance in a <em> vacuum </em>. This is why it is sometimes referred to as the <em> permittivity of free space </em> or the <em> vacuum permittivity</em>. If there is other matter in the vicinity of the source charge, then the magnitude of the electric field will be slightly different because the field needs to be <em> permitted</em> by matter. 
	</p>
	
	<p> 
	
	</p> 
	
	<p> 
Sometimes you will also see the electric field or force written in term of the <alert> electrostatic constant </alert> <m> k </m> instead of the permittivity constant. The relationship between the electrostatic constant and the permittivity constant is <me> k = \frac{1}{ 4 \pi \epsilon_0} = 9.0 \times 10^9 \frac{\mathrm{C^2}}{\mathrm{Nm^2}}</me>. It will simplify future calculations if we get used to writing fields in terms of the permittivity constant, but either notation is equivalent numerically. 
	</p> 
	
	
	<exercises>
		<title>
		Parallels in Gravity
		</title>
	</exercises>
	<p>
	We previously alluded that mass, like charge, physically alters the space around it which we call the <em> gravitational field </em>. Recall the definition of <xref ref="def_gravitational-field" text="title"/> and the definition of <xref ref="def_gravitational-force" text="title"/>.

	Formulating the gravitational force in terms of the gravitational field allows us to determine the acceleration due to gravity for any body of mass and at any distance from that body. Note the units of the Gravitational constant and then recall the units of the electrostatic constant <m> k </m>. Do you notice any similarities?
	</p> 

